<TITLE> Hasina seeks to remove legal barriers to overseas treatment </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, June 8 (bdnews24.com)Sheikh Hasina's lawyers Sunday appealed to a special judge to spare the former prime minister from a legal binding to appear in court in person in the barge-mounted power plants corruption case. The court is expected to rule on the appeal Monday. Lawyers said the step was taken to remove legal barriers to a plan to send the Awami League president abroad for better medical treatment. After receipt of the appeal, judge Md Feroz Alam of the special judge's court-1 at the Sangsad Bhaban discussed with the lawyers of state and defence sides at 5.45pm. Hasina's lawyer advocate Kamrul Islam told bdnews24.com, "We have appealed to the court to exempt Sheikh Hasina from personal appearance in court in the barge mounted power plants case." Hasina's another lawyer advocate Abdul Mannan Khan said: "Sheikh Hasina is seriously ill. She needs to be sent abroad for better treatment. That's why we have appealed to the court." Earlier, Supreme Court Bar Association president barrister Shafiq Ahmed, advocate Shahara Khatun, barrister Fazle Noor Tapash went to the special jail and met with Hasina. After the meeting with Hasina, they went to the special judge's court. In the judge's room in the discussion on the matter state chief counsel ABM Sharfuddin Khan Mukul, Md Shahid Sarder and other lawyers participated. bdnews24.
